n wisdom used to be that training in 2 weapon skills was a sure way to be a gimp.  But given the recent changes to armor bonuses, it is starting to look sensible (of course, this may be a pointless discussion since Mythic will probably alter the armor stats many, many more times).<br><br>Since spellcrafting will allow you to add plus skill points to weapons and armor, the possibility of getting to +11 at lvl 50 from items to almost all your stats is very reasonable.  +11 Stealth is easy, cause stealth items are plentiful, +11 envenom is simply DF jewel, epic gloves, +2 from armor, +11 to slash/thrust is no problem either if you wield 2 player made plus +5 to slash or thrust weaps.  The recent herald article on spell crafting gave an example where you could add +5 to a weap skill on a 10th lvl high qual player made weapon without overcharging.  Its gonna be expensive, but doable.  All you need is a ring of granite enhancement or +1 slash or thrust on a piece of armor and you hit +11 to slash/thrust.  <br><br>Add another +3 to everything with Realm Rank 4 and your total to stats is +14.  Which makes me consider the following template:<br><br>Stealth      36+14=50<br>Slash         36+14=50<br>Thrust       36+14=50<br>Envenom    36+14=50<br>CS            44 +3 = 47 (maybe a point or 2 more from items)<br>DW           10 + 3 = 13 (again, maybe a bit more with items, not crazy about DW anyway).<br><br>Supposedly over 50 envenom or stealth is useless, so your ok there.  CS at 44 should allow you to get 3 of the 4 style evade chain and PA, CD, SS as well.  Good PA cap too.<br><br>Weapon damage should be very good as well.  100% spec = 100%-150% avg. damage.  Since it has been said many times that spec over 100% does very little, a one weapon spec inf with 64 slash or thrust will not hit that much harder then you.  <br><br>The only issue here is whether or not being able to use the right weapon for the job is worth the cost of not having the high end slash/thrust styles.<br><br>I think it may be worth it.  <br><br>A thrust only or slash only inf may have a super high weapon skill in his chosen weapon type and access to high lvl styles like dragonfang (if a thruster), but against an armor type with a high resist, like thrust v.s. leather, damage output will be reduced by a whopping 30%!!!  <br><br>If he was a slash/thrust inf, he may have a slightly lower weapon damage in whatever weapon he choses to use because his spec is 50 and not 64.  However, instead of a 30% damage penalty against some armors, he will get a 15% bonus.  <br><br>I think that this would more than make up for the loss of the higher end styles and whatever minor benefit you get out of an over 100% weapon spec.  <br><br>At the moment, I am a thrust only inf.  I am not yet lvl 50 and don't have dragonfang, so I am not speaking form experience, but I would think that the primary benefit of the 9 second stun is simply that for a few combat rounds I can't get hit by my stunned enemy.  When you consider that all things being equal it will take a thruster 45% longer to take down a leather wearing enemy than a slasher would (15% bonus v.s. 30% penalty), the benefit is probably not worth it.  The thruster will take more hits as a result of the longer duration of the fight then he will avoid by being able to stun his enemy with dragon fang.<br><br>The only time I would regret not being a thrust only inf would probably be against something like chain, where the option to use slash would not help me and I would lose dragonfang (and a bit of damage output because I am 50 spec, not 64).  <br><br>Its a tough choice, but when I consider that an even con shadowblade will have a 45% damage advantage over me, which basically means I am dead, it seems logical to go slash/thrust.  And since, I already have a bag full of weapons with diff poisons, delays, etc. that I switch constantly based on the situation, adding some slash weapons won't really bother me that much more.  <br><br>P.S.  There is one other solution to the current armor resist changes.  Might be even better then a 2 weap spec template.  <br><br>Get a player made/spellcrafted suit of leather armor with super high slash resists.  That herald article said that it may be possible to get a total of 50% worth of resists with spellcrafting.  Even if you got only 30%, the slash leather wearer would only have a net 15% advantage which is reasonable.  Of course its possible he could have additional thrust resists from spellcrafting too, but since he already has a 30% resist from armor type, its not likely any leather wearer will have invested much in thrust resists.  <br><br> <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/uaach.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aach</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/28/02 6:02:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3821.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The &quot;Thrash&quot; template</span><hr size=1> Resist cap is (level / 2) +1 = 26 @ L50<br><br>Part of the evaluation here is that resists are going to to be common with spellcrafting.  It can be expected that people will enchant items in such a way as to offset their weakness and it may be posible for them to manufacture counter intuitive vulnerabilty.<br><br>E.g. I enchant +26 slash resist and leather is (for the sake of argument)  - 10 slash under the new rules.  My total resist is +16 slash.  If I ignore my crush resist it will languish at, say, 5 doubled to 10.  You'd expect that slash was how to kill assassins but in this instance crush is better.<br><br>This example is not absurd - assassins rarely face crush damage and very regularly face slash (perhapse more so after the patch).<br><br>My split spec worked very well untill epics came allong when suddenly I was getting a negative with slash against leather.  My oponant was getting a 15% negative but having a higher weaponskill and using a dex based weapon offset that.<br><br>Thrust vs Chain is still very viable but chain wearers are much tougher and while my damage is not gimped in comparison to a full thrust spec the extra time it takes to kill is significant. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/unage42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nage42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/28/02 7:10:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3821.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The &quot;Thrash&quot; template</span><hr size=1> Jebus, for an SB you choose to go _5_-spec if you want to be general but blow alot of your power to round yourself out.<br><br>Infs can be a pretty well setup _6_-spec... is there any doubt that this proves that Infs have just more points than they know what to do with (read: you don't even have to pick what you want to be strong at, you can be strong at everything).<br><br>Of course it's just class envy.... but I mean... comeon. <p>Cheers,<BR><BR>Steppin Razor, BORS/Mid [Lvl 45 5-spec SB (mostly good at all, master of none)]<BR>{Appeal to all Infs out there to drop their Buffbot handjobs... you don't need it, not by a mile}<BR>http://www.geocities.com/nage42/Steppin_Razor.html</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/utakofmidgard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>TakofMidgard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/29/02 6:32:56 am)</font><br>